      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Margaret L. Coit (1919-2003) was an American historian.  Her books include biographies of Andrew Jackson, Bernard Baruch, and John C. Calhoun as well as more general historical works.  She also taught at Fairleigh Dickinson University, the University of Colorado, and at numerous workshops.</p><p>Bernard Baruch (1870-1965) was an American financier, stock investor, philanthropist, statesman, and political consultant.  Among others, he advised U.S. Presidents Woodrow Wilson and Franklin D. Roosevelt on economic matters.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Margaret L. Coit Papers</emph> consist of manuscript drafts,
            including deleted pages and galleys of <emph render="italic">Mr. Baruch</emph>, her
            biography of Bernard Baruch. According to correspondence in our files, Ms Coit had
            completed the manuscript of her book when a falling-out with Baruch forced her to
            rewrite it. The manuscript version thus differs considerably from the final version
            published by Houghton Mifflin.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>The original manuscript of<emph render="italic"> Mr. Baruch</emph> and three revisions
            are followed by the publisher's corrected galley and the final proof copy.</p>
      </arrangement>
      
